  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This rebellious speech of Gaal was reported to Abimelech by the town-prefect Zebul, who sent messengers to him בּתרמה, either with deceit (תּרמה from רמה), i.e., employing deceit, inasmuch as he had listened to the speech quietly and with apparent assent, or \"in Tormah,\" the name of a place, תּרמה being a misspelling for ארמה  equals  ארוּמה (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 9:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The Sept. and Chaldee take the word as an appellative  equals  ἐν κρυφῇ, secretly; so also do Rashi and most of the earlier commentators, whilst R. Kimchi the elder has decided in favour of the second rendering as a proper name. As the word only occurs here, it is impossible to decide with certainty in favour of either view. צרים הנּם, behold they stir up the city against thee (צרים from צוּר in the sense of צרר). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
